00:02:54.310 --> 00:02:57.270
DDS is the state agency that's responsible

00:02:57.270 --> 00:02:59.870
for overseeing the coordination
and provision of services

00:02:59.870 --> 00:03:04.870
and supports for now
over 333,000 individuals,

00:03:05.210 --> 00:03:07.930
Californians with
developmental disabilities.

00:03:07.930 --> 00:03:11.660
And we contract with 21 regional centers,

00:03:11.660 --> 00:03:14.480
nonprofit private organizations

00:03:14.480 --> 00:03:17.960
who are geographically
located across the state

00:03:17.960 --> 00:03:22.150
to provide those local services
and supports to individuals.

00:03:22.150 --> 00:03:24.550
And all the services and
supports are provided

00:03:24.550 --> 00:03:27.660
in accordance with the Lanterman Act.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:30.170
Just for some general information,

00:03:30.170 --> 00:03:31.650
in this current fiscal year,

00:03:31.650 --> 00:03:34.370
the budget for the
Developmental Services System

00:03:34.370 --> 00:03:37.650
is $7.4 billion, and the governor's budget

00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:39.590
for next fiscal year '19-20

00:03:39.590 --> 00:03:44.120
includes $7.8 billion for the system.

00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:46.200
And the 21 regional centers employ

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:49.490
about 7,300 personnel and operate

00:03:49.490 --> 00:03:52.770
in over 70 different offices
throughout the state,

00:03:52.770 --> 00:03:54.850
which is really kind of the
heart of the Lanterman Act

00:03:54.850 --> 00:03:59.850
in that local presence and
support of communities.

00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:04.970
And there are over
423,000 service providers

00:04:04.970 --> 00:04:09.420
including families,
and excluding families,

00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:13.373
about 43,000 service providers
throughout the state.

00:04:16.452 --> 00:04:18.917
I think this is a good
visual of the system

00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:24.513
that just shows kind
of how we are operated,

00:04:25.410 --> 00:04:27.140
and to just bring your attention

00:04:27.140 --> 00:04:31.020
to the state-operated services,
which I think historically

00:04:31.020 --> 00:04:34.030
folks have kind of
talked about DDS oversees

00:04:34.030 --> 00:04:35.540
the developmental centers.

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:38.870
We've changed our language
as the system is moving

00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:41.470
much more towards being an almost entirely

00:04:41.470 --> 00:04:43.400
community-based service system

00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:47.140
to saying state-operated versus
vendor-operated services.

00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:50.220
And through the department,
the state-operated services

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:53.240
include services to
individuals who are residing

00:04:53.240 --> 00:04:57.593
in developmental centers,
and as of December 2018,

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:02.797
Sonoma Developmental Center closed,

00:05:02.797 --> 00:05:04.580
and the last individual moved

00:05:04.580 --> 00:05:07.433
into their new home in
the community, and--

00:05:07.433 --> 00:05:10.600
(audience applauding)

00:05:11.452 --> 00:05:16.197
Over the next several, over at
least the next year or more,

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:20.410
about 118 additional individuals

00:05:20.410 --> 00:05:23.170
from Fairview Developmental Center

00:05:23.170 --> 00:05:25.920
and Porterville Developmental Center's

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:29.160
general treatment area will
be moving into the community.

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:32.980
So similar to national trends, our system,

00:05:32.980 --> 00:05:35.820
again, is really moving
to be an almost entirely

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:38.423
community-based service system.

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:44.980
And I'm not sure how much people

00:05:45.030 --> 00:05:47.730
have kind of thought about
that as a historic event

00:05:47.730 --> 00:05:51.500
in our state, but in
1968, about 13,000 people

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:56.160
were living in developmental
centers, and as of January,

00:05:59.010 --> 00:06:00.510
there were less than 400

00:06:00.510 --> 00:06:02.220
people living in development centers.

00:06:02.220 --> 00:06:06.840
So that has been a push of the system

00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:08.970
since the Lanterman Act came into effect

00:06:08.970 --> 00:06:11.640
and really was focused on developing

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:13.420
a robust community service system.

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:16.490
And then of course, we
contract as a department

00:06:16.490 --> 00:06:19.600
with the 21 regional centers who in turn

00:06:20.550 --> 00:06:25.350
provide local case
management and who vendor

00:06:25.350 --> 00:06:27.210
the providers who provide the services

00:06:27.210 --> 00:06:29.063
and supports to individuals.

00:06:30.550 --> 00:06:34.158
Kind of as key responsibilities for DDS

00:06:34.158 --> 00:06:37.830
is that broad policy and
statewide leadership,

00:06:37.830 --> 00:06:41.840
setting priorities, setting
standards and procedures

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:43.130
that kind of guide the operation

00:06:43.130 --> 00:06:45.860
of the service system across the state,

00:06:45.860 --> 00:06:49.790
monitoring service delivery, and providing

00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:52.560
technical support when issues come up,

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:55.160
providing support to regional centers,

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:59.253
the provider community, and
the individuals we serve.

00:07:01.780 --> 00:07:03.883
Many of you work at regional centers,

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.030
and here I think what's
really critical to say

00:07:08.030 --> 00:07:11.000
is that the face of our service system

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:12.970
is really the service coordinator.

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:14.960
That is the person who families meet,

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:17.497
that's the face of our
entire service system,

00:07:17.497 --> 00:07:20.840
and that relationship that's built

00:07:20.840 --> 00:07:25.000
to ensure that individuals
and their families

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:26.850
get the service sand supports they need

00:07:26.850 --> 00:07:29.470
and again, kind of that foundation

00:07:29.470 --> 00:07:31.940
of the Lanterman Act,
that 21 regional centers

00:07:31.940 --> 00:07:34.790
are geographically located to understand

00:07:34.790 --> 00:07:37.190
and support the unique
needs of their community.

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:43.160
So the services include
intake and assessment,

00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:45.300
helping individuals
advocate for themselves

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:47.910
and also helping advocate for them,

00:07:47.910 --> 00:07:51.320
assisting with access to resources

00:07:51.320 --> 00:07:52.750
that are available in the community,

00:07:52.750 --> 00:07:56.883
and of course for funding
services that individuals need.

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:01.410
And then just briefly
touching on eligibility

00:08:01.410 --> 00:08:05.410
for regional center services,

00:08:05.410 --> 00:08:08.030
it's all up here on the slide.

00:08:08.030 --> 00:08:13.030
You're eligible if prior to age of 18

00:08:13.450 --> 00:08:15.920
you have a qualifying disability

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:19.120
that's expected to be
lifelong and in addition

00:08:19.120 --> 00:08:23.670
that is substantially disabling for you

00:08:23.670 --> 00:08:27.270
and provides significant
functional limitations

00:08:27.270 --> 00:08:30.233
in several areas of major life activity.

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:35.893
So now onto the more
exciting (chuckles) data.

00:08:37.540 --> 00:08:38.830
Whoa.

00:08:38.830 --> 00:08:42.560
- Okay, so we have 21 regional
centers across the state.

00:08:42.560 --> 00:08:46.410
Each regional center represents
its own catchment area.

00:08:46.410 --> 00:08:49.500
So the regional centers
are geographically diverse

00:08:49.500 --> 00:08:52.640
as well as in terms of their population.

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:55.290
Our smallest regional
center is Redwood Coast.

00:08:55.290 --> 00:08:57.720
They serve 3,900 individuals,

00:08:57.720 --> 00:08:59.460
and our largest regional center

00:08:59.460 --> 00:09:01.680
is Inland Regional Center who serves

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:06.550
35,500 individuals as
of January of this year.

00:09:06.550 --> 00:09:08.930
And you can see, there's a wide range

00:09:08.930 --> 00:09:13.363
across all 21 in terms of how
many individuals they serve.

00:09:14.920 --> 00:09:17.690
Okay, in terms of our
total state population,

00:09:17.690 --> 00:09:21.890
over the last 10 years,
we've seen a 42% increase

00:09:21.890 --> 00:09:24.270
on the number of
individuals that we serve.

00:09:24.270 --> 00:09:28.950
So in 2008, our total was 232,000.

00:09:28.950 --> 00:09:33.570
As of this year, we're at
333,000 individuals total.

00:09:33.570 --> 00:09:35.730
And our individuals are broken down

00:09:35.730 --> 00:09:37.270
into two groups on the graph here.

00:09:37.270 --> 00:09:40.190
In gray, you'll see
our Early Start kiddos.

00:09:40.190 --> 00:09:42.810
These are children under the age of three.

00:09:42.810 --> 00:09:45.530
And then in blue, these
are our Lanterman-eligible

00:09:45.530 --> 00:09:48.290
individuals, so these are
individuals age three and up

00:09:48.290 --> 00:09:51.163
who meet the criteria that
LeeAnn just described.

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:54.340
And in addition to that,
we have individuals

00:09:54.340 --> 00:09:57.490
who are currently under
assessment at the regional centers

00:09:57.490 --> 00:09:59.890
to receive eligibility
for either Early Start

00:09:59.890 --> 00:10:03.160
or Lanterman regional center services.

00:10:03.160 --> 00:10:07.950
And in January, we had 12,500 individuals

00:10:07.950 --> 00:10:10.430
who are currently in the assessment phase.

00:10:10.430 --> 00:10:12.090
So the regional centers are really busy

00:10:12.090 --> 00:10:15.320
in terms of bringing
individuals in to assess them

00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:19.310
for eligibility and then
making them eligible

00:10:19.310 --> 00:10:21.323
and coordinating all of their services.

00:10:23.700 --> 00:10:27.210
Okay, so let's look deeper

00:10:27.210 --> 00:10:29.610
at what our population looks like.

00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:32.900
So in terms of their living arrangements,

00:10:32.900 --> 00:10:34.920
over the last 10 years,
we've seen an increase

00:10:34.920 --> 00:10:37.070
in the number of
individuals who are residing

00:10:37.070 --> 00:10:40.630
in the home of their
family, parent, or guardian,

00:10:40.630 --> 00:10:42.800
and we've seen a decrease in almost

00:10:42.800 --> 00:10:44.230
every other residence type.

00:10:44.230 --> 00:10:46.480
So you can see at the very top there

00:10:46.480 --> 00:10:47.680
the percentage of individuals

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:49.730
in developmental centers is going down.

00:10:49.730 --> 00:10:51.890
Obviously we're moving them
out into the community,

00:10:51.890 --> 00:10:55.590
so that was expected,
but we've seen actually

00:10:55.590 --> 00:10:58.330
a 60% growth in the number of consumers

00:10:58.330 --> 00:11:00.390
who are living in the home

00:11:00.390 --> 00:11:02.700
due to our increasing
caseload of children.

00:11:02.700 --> 00:11:05.250
So we're seeing a large growth

00:11:05.250 --> 00:11:08.210
in the number of individuals
under 22 who we serve,

00:11:08.210 --> 00:11:10.030
and obviously most of
them are gonna be living

00:11:10.030 --> 00:11:13.050
in the home of their parent or guardian.

00:11:13.050 --> 00:11:15.970
However, across the
lifespan, we're also seeing

00:11:15.970 --> 00:11:18.410
an increase in the number
of adults who we serve

00:11:18.410 --> 00:11:19.960
who are choosing to live at home.

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:22.270
We're seeing that more often
than we did 10 years ago,

00:11:22.270 --> 00:11:25.160
and you can see that in the
bars on the bottom there.

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:28.120
So 10 years ago, 74%
were living in the home

00:11:28.120 --> 00:11:29.850
of a parent, family, or guardian.

00:11:29.850 --> 00:11:34.133
And in 2018, it was 80% of who
the regional centers serve.

00:11:35.750 --> 00:11:37.950
Okay, we're also seeing
a change in the landscape

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:40.940
of the racial and ethnic makeup

00:11:40.940 --> 00:11:43.330
of the individuals in our system,

00:11:43.330 --> 00:11:45.230
and this is similar to what we see

00:11:45.230 --> 00:11:48.110
across the state of California in general,

00:11:48.110 --> 00:11:51.820
but the largest shift has been in Hispanic

00:11:51.820 --> 00:11:54.030
or Latino individuals that we serve.

00:11:54.030 --> 00:11:56.430
So we've seen an increase in individuals

00:11:56.430 --> 00:11:58.830
who identify as Hispanic or Latino.

00:11:58.830 --> 00:12:02.050
10 years ago, they were
34% of our population,

00:12:02.050 --> 00:12:06.390
and now they are 39%,
whereas we've seen a decrease

00:12:06.390 --> 00:12:08.550
in the share of individuals who identify

00:12:08.550 --> 00:12:13.550
as white or Caucasian, 39% in 2008,

00:12:14.270 --> 00:12:17.833
now they represent 31%, so
their share has gone down.

00:12:19.360 --> 00:12:22.270
I should also note, half
of the Hispanic population

00:12:22.270 --> 00:12:24.810
is in the three-to-21-year group,

00:12:24.810 --> 00:12:29.560
so we see a large increase,
particularly in childhood

00:12:29.560 --> 00:12:32.670
for that ethnic group,
whereas only a third

00:12:32.670 --> 00:12:36.903
of the white or Caucasian group
is in that same age range.

00:12:38.040 --> 00:12:40.740
So we see more of the share of individuals

00:12:40.740 --> 00:12:42.940
who are white are
actually adults right now.

00:12:44.303 --> 00:12:47.090
And then overall, there
are at least 23 ethnicities

00:12:47.090 --> 00:12:49.520
and 45 different languages identified

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:52.070
by our consumers across the state.

00:12:52.070 --> 00:12:54.670
So we're seeing a big shift in terms

00:12:54.670 --> 00:12:56.520
of the racial and ethnic makeup

00:12:56.520 --> 00:12:58.340
of the individuals that we serve,

00:12:58.340 --> 00:13:00.390
and I think that that's
an important indicator

00:13:00.390 --> 00:13:05.070
of making sure that our
services and supports

00:13:05.070 --> 00:13:08.550
are all going to be
linguistically accessible

00:13:08.550 --> 00:13:12.060
to individuals and culturally
sensitive and appropriate

00:13:12.060 --> 00:13:14.550
for the children and adults that we serve.

00:13:14.550 --> 00:13:17.010
So we will probably see some shift

00:13:17.010 --> 00:13:18.670
in the way that our system is gonna need

00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:23.670
to be supporting individuals
of all ethnicities.

00:13:25.390 --> 00:13:28.690
Okay, we're seeing some changes in terms

00:13:28.690 --> 00:13:31.600
of the ages of the individuals
that we're serving,

00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:33.380
and we're seeing that individuals

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:35.320
with disabilities are living longer.

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:39.990
So 10 years ago, 8% of our
population was 52 or older.

00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:44.763
Today it's 10%, so that group
is increasing, which is great.

00:13:46.870 --> 00:13:51.870
Okay, all right, in terms of
the five diagnostic groups

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:55.590
that are eligible for services,

00:13:55.590 --> 00:13:57.660
those include Autism, Cerebral Palsy,

00:13:57.660 --> 00:14:00.960
Epilepsy, Intellectual
Disability, and then Other,

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:02.770
which is our fifth
category, and this would be

00:14:02.770 --> 00:14:05.430
disabilities that are similar in nature

00:14:05.430 --> 00:14:07.970
to an intellectual disability.

00:14:07.970 --> 00:14:10.300
We're seeing changes
in the share of these,

00:14:10.300 --> 00:14:13.010
and I do wanna note that these aren't

00:14:13.010 --> 00:14:15.710
mutually exclusive categorizations,

00:14:15.710 --> 00:14:18.340
so an individual could have
more than one diagnosis,

00:14:18.340 --> 00:14:20.560
and they're gonna be
counted more than once here.

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:22.460
So if you're trying to add up the bars,

00:14:22.460 --> 00:14:25.283
they may add up to more
than 100%, and that's why.

00:14:26.510 --> 00:14:29.900
But the key takeaway here
is over the last 10 years,

00:14:29.900 --> 00:14:32.180
we've seen an increase in
the share of individuals

00:14:32.180 --> 00:14:34.430
who have a diagnosis of autism.

00:14:34.430 --> 00:14:37.520
So they've risen from 19% to 38%,

00:14:37.520 --> 00:14:40.210
whereas the share of all
other diagnostic groups

00:14:40.210 --> 00:14:43.173
have been declining
over the last 10 years.

00:14:45.150 --> 00:14:48.660
Okay, and so looking
deeper at the population

00:14:48.660 --> 00:14:52.200
of individuals with autism, these would be

00:14:52.200 --> 00:14:55.030
the individuals with autism 10 years ago,

00:14:55.030 --> 00:14:57.320
in 2008, in blue, and then in orange,

00:14:57.320 --> 00:15:00.790
this is 2018, so you can see a big rise

00:15:00.790 --> 00:15:03.583
in the number of individuals
with autism in our system.

