are under 22, so most of those folks

00:16:00.830 --> 00:16:03.603
who have autism that we're
serving are children.

00:16:04.470 --> 00:16:06.760
So that's gonna have some
important implications

00:16:06.760 --> 00:16:10.160
for how we serve these
individuals as they age.

00:16:10.160 --> 00:16:12.010
We're gonna see a sharp increase

00:16:12.010 --> 00:16:13.810
in the number of individuals with autism

00:16:13.810 --> 00:16:15.240
who are gonna be transitioning

00:16:15.240 --> 00:16:17.853
from the school system
into young adulthood.

00:16:18.996 --> 00:16:20.860
And looking at the
graph on the right here,

00:16:20.860 --> 00:16:23.070
this is all of the
individuals that we serve

00:16:23.070 --> 00:16:28.030
who are under 22, and autism makes up 60%,

00:16:28.030 --> 00:16:31.440
so they're making up more
than half of the children

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:33.913
that we serve in our service system.

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:39.920
Okay, so our increase in autism

00:16:39.920 --> 00:16:41.700
has pretty strong implication

00:16:41.700 --> 00:16:44.510
for our service delivery
system and being prepared

00:16:44.510 --> 00:16:47.910
to support individuals
who are on the spectrum.

00:16:47.910 --> 00:16:49.840
This has become a focus of our department

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:51.720
and probably the primary reason

00:16:51.720 --> 00:16:55.330
for my position in the department,

00:16:55.330 --> 00:16:57.500
but this isn't precluding our work

00:16:57.500 --> 00:16:59.970
for all of the other diagnostic types.

00:16:59.970 --> 00:17:03.110
Our department is still
dedicated to serving

00:17:03.110 --> 00:17:05.750
individuals of all
development disabilities,

00:17:05.750 --> 00:17:08.820
and the services and
supports that we develop

00:17:08.820 --> 00:17:13.240
and prioritize are gonna
be with the thought in mind

00:17:13.240 --> 00:17:15.680
that we wanna serve everyone that we can

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:17.163
in the best way possible.

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:20.383
Okay, you ready?

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:33.230
- So as Lauren went through, you can see

00:17:33.230 --> 00:17:35.210
a lot of the changing demographics

00:17:35.210 --> 00:17:38.820
of the individuals we serve,
and so as we're identifying

00:17:38.820 --> 00:17:43.070
those changing, the
trends that are changing

00:17:43.070 --> 00:17:47.030
in our population, we're
also trying to learn

00:17:47.030 --> 00:17:49.750
what their changing needs
and expectations are

00:17:49.750 --> 00:17:52.330
of the service system, and
I think one of the things

00:17:52.330 --> 00:17:55.530
that the department has
really spent a lotta time on

00:17:55.530 --> 00:17:58.260
and continues to be committed
to is community engagement

00:17:58.260 --> 00:18:00.700
so that we can have ongoing discussions

00:18:00.700 --> 00:18:04.120
with stakeholders to learn
about what their needs

00:18:04.120 --> 00:18:07.790
and expectations are
from the service system.

00:18:07.790 --> 00:18:12.300
So in addition to just kind
of the national trends,

00:18:12.300 --> 00:18:17.300
particularly in their focus
on community-based services

00:18:17.590 --> 00:18:22.180
and decreasing or closing
developmental centers,

00:18:22.180 --> 00:18:25.240
we are also relying on that information

00:18:25.240 --> 00:18:26.930
that we're gathering from stakeholders

00:18:26.930 --> 00:18:29.600
to determine what the
department's priorities

00:18:29.600 --> 00:18:33.710
and initiatives are in these coming years,

00:18:33.710 --> 00:18:38.377
because as we see and as
Director Bargmann would say,

00:18:38.377 --> 00:18:41.660
"We have new architects
of our service system,"

00:18:41.660 --> 00:18:43.360
and so we're listening to them to see

00:18:43.360 --> 00:18:45.167
what that service system
needs to look like

00:18:45.167 --> 00:18:47.410
and the expectations of what life is like

00:18:47.410 --> 00:18:48.720
in the community where you live,

00:18:48.720 --> 00:18:51.330
what you do during the
day, the relationships

00:18:51.330 --> 00:18:53.740
that you develop all
have to be acknowledged.

00:18:53.740 --> 00:18:57.420
And so as far as the
priorities and initiatives,

00:18:57.420 --> 00:18:59.410
the first thing I just wanna touch on

00:18:59.410 --> 00:19:02.062
is that developmental center closure.

00:19:02.062 --> 00:19:04.420
I talked about it a
little bit, but in 2012,

00:19:04.420 --> 00:19:06.840
there was a moratorium on anyone

00:19:06.840 --> 00:19:08.000
moving into the developmental center,

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:13.000
and then in 2015, there
was the closure plan

00:19:13.690 --> 00:19:16.000
for three of the developmental centers,

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:17.630
Sonoma, which closed in December,

00:19:17.630 --> 00:19:18.990
Fairview Developmental Center

00:19:18.990 --> 00:19:20.990
and Porterville Developmental Center's

00:19:20.990 --> 00:19:23.180
general treatment area which are scheduled

00:19:24.140 --> 00:19:29.063
in that closure plan to close in 2021.

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:37.800
By the end of 2021, then,
and much likely very,

00:19:39.080 --> 00:19:43.840
and likely more, pluh, likely
sooner (laughs) than 2021,

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:48.490
given that 118 people are
actively transitioning

00:19:48.490 --> 00:19:53.090
into the community, we are really focused

00:19:53.090 --> 00:19:56.660
on community development
and what we need to be doing

00:19:56.660 --> 00:20:00.440
to not only develop
resources for the individuals

00:20:00.440 --> 00:20:02.950
transitioning from development centers

00:20:02.950 --> 00:20:05.570
into the community,
which of course has been

00:20:05.570 --> 00:20:08.120
the major focus over the
past couple of years,

00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:11.260
but also to be developing resources

00:20:11.260 --> 00:20:15.130
for individuals who never have lived in

00:20:15.130 --> 00:20:18.880
or never would have lived
in a developmental center,

00:20:18.880 --> 00:20:22.240
particularly those individuals
who have very complex

00:20:22.240 --> 00:20:25.613
medical, behavioral,
and psychiatric needs.

00:20:26.757 --> 00:20:31.660
And so through the Developmental
Service Task Force,

00:20:31.660 --> 00:20:33.630
which is a statewide task force,

00:20:33.630 --> 00:20:37.880
through other community engagement,

00:20:37.880 --> 00:20:40.540
we have developed new service models.

00:20:40.540 --> 00:20:43.800
Residential has been the primary focus

00:20:43.800 --> 00:20:47.010
to assist in having people
have good-quality lives

00:20:47.010 --> 00:20:50.210
in the community and homes
that address their challenging

00:20:50.210 --> 00:20:52.920
medical and behavioral
and psychiatric needs.

00:20:52.920 --> 00:20:57.920
But also importantly looking
at what those resource,

00:20:57.920 --> 00:21:00.160
what that resource development
or community development

00:21:00.160 --> 00:21:03.310
needs to look like given how many people

00:21:03.310 --> 00:21:06.630
are living at home and want
to stay living at home.

00:21:06.630 --> 00:21:09.520
So I think the most important note here

00:21:09.520 --> 00:21:12.780
is that our community
development has to meet

00:21:12.780 --> 00:21:15.300
the changing needs of
the people that we serve,

00:21:15.300 --> 00:21:18.390
and it has to keep pace with those needs,

00:21:18.390 --> 00:21:23.333
which I think is something
that we continue to work on.

00:21:25.590 --> 00:21:28.220
In addition to that, I
think one of the things

00:21:28.220 --> 00:21:30.340
that has come up as a system issue

00:21:30.340 --> 00:21:32.940
is how do we do that in
not only a timely way

00:21:32.940 --> 00:21:36.590
but in a sustainable way,
and we don't have time

00:21:36.590 --> 00:21:40.590
in our short time here,
but one of the barriers

00:21:40.590 --> 00:21:43.220
potentially to developing needed resources

00:21:43.220 --> 00:21:46.350
is making sure that providers
have sustainable rates.

00:21:46.350 --> 00:21:48.960
And so I just wanna quickly mention

00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:53.960
the department's requirement
to engage in a rate study

00:21:54.760 --> 00:21:56.850
and that you can get a lot of information

00:21:56.850 --> 00:21:58.630
about the results of the rate study

00:21:58.630 --> 00:22:03.343
and some of the proposed new
rate models on the DDS website.

00:22:04.560 --> 00:22:07.210
As far as the Safety
Net, as a result of input

00:22:07.210 --> 00:22:10.120
from that Developmental
Services Task Force

00:22:10.120 --> 00:22:12.130
and other stakeholder engagement,

00:22:12.130 --> 00:22:15.040
in 2017, the department
released a Safety Net

00:22:15.040 --> 00:22:18.030
or crisis plan, and the focus of that

00:22:18.030 --> 00:22:22.330
Safety Net was really
ensuring that crisis services

00:22:22.330 --> 00:22:24.440
and services that would prevent a crisis

00:22:24.440 --> 00:22:27.630
were developed or
expanded in the community

00:22:27.630 --> 00:22:30.270
to support people moving out
of the developmental center

00:22:30.270 --> 00:22:34.810
and also, again, to
ensure that individuals

00:22:34.810 --> 00:22:38.200
who are living at home can stay at home

00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:40.240
and not be placed in more
restrictive settings.

00:22:40.240 --> 00:22:42.120
So the Safety Net Plan itself,

00:22:42.120 --> 00:22:45.120
which is not a one-time
document but an ongoing

00:22:45.120 --> 00:22:47.590
planning process has been looking at how

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:50.370
to develop crisis services,
mobile crisis services,

00:22:50.370 --> 00:22:53.800
acute crisis services
throughout the community

00:22:53.800 --> 00:22:57.270
as well as some of those
intensive support models

00:22:57.270 --> 00:22:59.320
in residential settings to help people

00:22:59.320 --> 00:23:02.383
so that they can avoid going
the more restrictive settings.

00:23:10.060 --> 00:23:12.990
It is really hard to
do these priority area

00:23:12.990 --> 00:23:17.250
that could take up their own
time in more than 30 minutes.

00:23:17.250 --> 00:23:20.880
The next one is home and
community-based services rules.

00:23:20.880 --> 00:23:23.590
In January 2014, the federal

00:23:23.590 --> 00:23:26.930
Centers for Medicare and
Medicaid issued new rules

00:23:26.930 --> 00:23:29.530
to enhance home and
community-based services,

00:23:29.530 --> 00:23:33.160
and those homes and programs have to meet

00:23:33.160 --> 00:23:36.120
those new criteria by March 2022

00:23:36.120 --> 00:23:39.540
to qualify for federal programming.

00:23:39.540 --> 00:23:41.980
And so in the past budget acts,

00:23:41.980 --> 00:23:44.910
there's been money
allocated to the department

00:23:44.910 --> 00:23:49.690
to assist providers in
changing their practices,

00:23:49.690 --> 00:23:51.960
changing whatever they need
to to come into compliance

00:23:51.960 --> 00:23:54.650
with those rules, and the final rule

00:23:54.650 --> 00:23:58.190
really focuses on what is very consistent

00:23:58.190 --> 00:23:59.650
and aligned with the Lanterman Act

00:23:59.650 --> 00:24:02.940
with regards to making
sure that individuals

00:24:02.940 --> 00:24:04.510
are integrated in their communities,

00:24:04.510 --> 00:24:08.420
have opportunities to
participate in their community,

00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:11.813
and have full access to the benefits

00:24:11.813 --> 00:24:13.963
of living in their community.

00:24:19.110 --> 00:24:22.170
The Self-Determination Program,

00:24:22.170 --> 00:24:26.640
Governor Brown signed that
into law in October 2013,

00:24:26.640 --> 00:24:30.050
and the department, and
the goal was establishing

00:24:30.050 --> 00:24:32.410
a statewide Self-Determination Project

00:24:32.410 --> 00:24:33.940
so that individuals and families

00:24:33.940 --> 00:24:35.300
could have more freedom and control

00:24:35.300 --> 00:24:38.090
and responsibility over
the services and supports

00:24:38.090 --> 00:24:39.850
that they receive in order to meet

00:24:39.850 --> 00:24:42.870
the objectives that they set forth

00:24:42.870 --> 00:24:45.310
in their Individual Program Plan,

00:24:45.310 --> 00:24:48.240
and so DDS has been working
the stakeholder advisory group

00:24:48.240 --> 00:24:50.150
over the past several years to develop

00:24:50.150 --> 00:24:53.080
the framework of that
Self-Determination Project.

00:24:53.080 --> 00:24:56.980
It did get approval from
CMS in June of last year,

00:24:56.980 --> 00:25:01.420
and so in the phase-in of the program,

00:25:01.420 --> 00:25:06.270
2,500 participants were
selected in October 2018,

00:25:06.270 --> 00:25:09.590
and now the process currently
is that regional centers

00:25:09.590 --> 00:25:13.130
and local advisory committees
are receiving training

00:25:13.130 --> 00:25:15.250
on how to conduct their own orientations

00:25:15.250 --> 00:25:17.510
in their local communities
with participants

00:25:17.510 --> 00:25:20.163
as the program is moving forward.

00:25:21.410 --> 00:25:24.830
For Competitive Integrated Employment,

00:25:24.830 --> 00:25:27.660
this effort really began in 2014,

00:25:27.660 --> 00:25:32.310
and it is an interdepartmental project

00:25:32.310 --> 00:25:34.020
with Department of Developmental Services,

00:25:34.020 --> 00:25:35.570
Department of Rehabilitation,

00:25:35.570 --> 00:25:37.880
and the Department of Education,

00:25:37.880 --> 00:25:40.830
and a variety of other stakeholders

00:25:40.830 --> 00:25:43.540
developing a blueprint for
community and integrated

00:25:43.540 --> 00:25:47.140
employment which was
released in May of 2016,

00:25:47.140 --> 00:25:49.010
and the purpose of that blueprint

00:25:49.010 --> 00:25:52.570
is to improve collaboration
between departments

00:25:52.570 --> 00:25:55.820
so that we can all help prepare

00:25:55.820 --> 00:25:58.420
and support individuals
who have intellectual

00:25:58.420 --> 00:26:00.550
and developmental disabilities

00:26:00.550 --> 00:26:05.550
to have opportunities and
to join the workforce.

00:26:06.700 --> 00:26:11.210
And it's really focused on
increasing those opportunities

00:26:11.210 --> 00:26:13.690
to prepare for and participate

00:26:13.690 --> 00:26:16.840
in competitive integrated employment,

00:26:16.840 --> 00:26:18.770
and just to make sure
that people are informed

00:26:18.770 --> 00:26:21.810
about the decisions, the
options that they really have

00:26:21.810 --> 00:26:23.880
to join the workforce
and what kind of supports

00:26:23.880 --> 00:26:26.840
they can get to prepare
for that transition to it

00:26:26.840 --> 00:26:30.660
after school and engage in it
throughout their adulthood.

00:26:30.660 --> 00:26:34.850
Since 2016, DDS has
implemented two programs

00:26:34.850 --> 00:26:37.720
that have had an impact on
a couple a thousand people

00:26:37.720 --> 00:26:41.010
to date, and those Paid Internship Program

00:26:41.010 --> 00:26:44.270
and competitive employment
incentive payment programs

00:26:44.270 --> 00:26:49.270
to help get people experience
with and into situations

00:26:49.840 --> 00:26:54.840
that lead towards integrated employment.

00:26:54.910 --> 00:26:58.260
And then the last priority
that we're gonna talk

00:26:58.260 --> 00:27:01.940
about today is the
Disparity Funds Project.

00:27:01.940 --> 00:27:04.440
Annually, the department
and regional centers

00:27:04.440 --> 00:27:07.710
collaborate to gather information

00:27:07.710 --> 00:27:09.570
through the purchase of service,

00:27:09.570 --> 00:27:13.000
and what over the years has been indicated

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:15.490
is that there are significant disparities

00:27:15.490 --> 00:27:19.650
that exist among some
regional center populations,

00:27:19.650 --> 00:27:23.540
particularly along the
lines of race and ethnicity.

00:27:23.540 --> 00:27:26.270
And in 2016, a section was added

00:27:26.270 --> 00:27:28.140
to the Welfare and Institutions Code

00:27:28.140 --> 00:27:30.890
allocating $11 million annually

00:27:30.890 --> 00:27:34.690
to the department to
assist regional centers

00:27:34.690 --> 00:27:38.920
in implementing strategies
that reduce those disparities.

00:27:38.920 --> 00:27:43.440
In budget acts since 2106,
that $11 million was expanded

00:27:43.440 --> 00:27:46.450
to fund projects through
the regional centers

00:27:46.450 --> 00:27:49.390
and also through
community-based organizations.

00:27:49.390 --> 00:27:54.390
And in the past fiscal year,
actually in this current

00:27:54.590 --> 00:27:58.680
fiscal year, '18-19, we
approved 70 projects,

00:27:58.680 --> 00:28:03.680
and 32 have just come to an end
at the end of December 2018,

00:28:04.750 --> 00:28:07.280
and so we're in the process of working

00:28:07.280 --> 00:28:09.990
with the regional centers on gathering

00:28:09.990 --> 00:28:13.150
outcome information and
being able to present

00:28:13.150 --> 00:28:15.160
that information to the community.

00:28:15.160 --> 00:28:16.620
But the projects have really focused

00:28:16.620 --> 00:28:19.730
on helping increase access to information

00:28:19.730 --> 00:28:22.290
about services through the
regional center system,

00:28:22.290 --> 00:28:24.790
providing assistance to families

00:28:24.790 --> 00:28:26.970
and individuals during the intake process,

00:28:26.970 --> 00:28:30.025
and just empowering people to understand

00:28:30.025 --> 00:28:33.853
the system and advocate
for their needed services.

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:39.130
And then finally, again,
just kind of, I know,

00:28:39.130 --> 00:28:42.848
a very high-level overview
with lots of details

00:28:42.848 --> 00:28:46.060
that hopefully would be
available on our website

00:28:46.060 --> 00:28:49.163
if you're interested in a
particular priority area.

00:28:50.260 --> 00:28:52.360
I think that one of the key things, again,

00:28:52.360 --> 00:28:55.530
in looking at the trends in our population

00:28:55.530 --> 00:28:57.300
is that we really are committed

00:28:57.300 --> 00:29:00.580
and want to hear from
our stakeholder groups

00:29:00.580 --> 00:29:02.700
and work collaboratively
with the regional centers

00:29:02.700 --> 00:29:05.440
to meet the changing needs, to keep pace

00:29:05.440 --> 00:29:07.740
with those changing needs so that people

00:29:07.740 --> 00:29:12.170
can have quality lives,
healthy and safe lives

00:29:12.170 --> 00:29:13.470
where they wanna live and be doing

00:29:13.470 --> 00:29:16.730
what they wanna do with their days,

00:29:16.730 --> 00:29:19.690
and we really hope that
just this high level

00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:22.220
has been useful to you.

00:29:22.220 --> 00:29:24.593
And again, on behalf of Director Bargmann,

00:29:24.593 --> 00:29:27.684
I wanna think for your
time and invitation.

00:29:27.684 --> 00:29:30.851
(audience applauding)

00:29:31.857 --> 00:29:32.690
Thank you.

